  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1956 (Money Laundering Control Act)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1957\n- The Patriot Act\n\n2. State Statutes:\n- Most states have their own money laundering prevention laws that complement federal statutes\n\nThese laws generally:\n- Define money laundering as a criminal offense\n- Establish reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Mandate suspicious transaction reporting\n- Impose significant criminal and civil penalties\n- Provide mechanisms for asset forfeiture\n\nFederal statutes primarily cover:\n- Concealing proceeds from illegal activities\n- Conducting financial transactions with criminal proceeds\n- Transporting monetary instruments illegally\n- Engaging in transactions designed to promote criminal activity\n\nPenalties can include:\n- Substantial fines\n- Imprisonment\n- Asset seizure\n- Civil penalties\n\nEnforcement is typically conducted by agencies like:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation",
